==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Curvet
<hw>Cur"vet</hw> <pr>(k⟦ucir⟧r"v?t ⟦or⟧ k⟦ucir⟧r-v?t"; 277)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>corvet</ets>, It.<ets>corvetta</ets>: cf.
F. <ets>courbette</ets>. See <er>Curve</er>, and cf.
<er>Corvetto</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Man.)</fld> <def>A
particular leap of a horse, when he raises both his fore legs at once,
equally advanced, and, as his fore legs are falling, raises his hind
legs, so that all his legs are in the air at once.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A prank; a frolic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Curvet</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Curvet
<hw>Cur"vet</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Curveted</conjf> or <conjf>-vetted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Curveting</conjf> or <conjf>-vetting</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[Cf. It. <ets>corvettare</ets>. See <er>Curvet</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a curvet; to leap; to
bound.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Oft and high he did <xex>curvet</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Drayton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To leap and frisk; to frolic.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Curvet</ent>⟦br⟧

